      <abstract>
        <p>William Betz letter on Times admissions about coverage of Wen Ho Lee national security case; suggests paper recommit to sensitivity about individual rights</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Your Sept. 26 note ''From the Editors'' about The Times's coverage of the Wen Ho Lee case says a public accounting was warranted because of ''the stakes involved, a man's liberty and reputation.''</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Your Sept. 26 note ''From the Editors'' about The Times's coverage of the Wen Ho Lee case says a public accounting was warranted because of ''the stakes involved, a man's liberty and reputation.''</p>
        <p>In a country in which two million people are incarcerated and whose prison system is perhaps well on the way to becoming the country's biggest business, the time might be right for a recommitment by The Times to its traditional sensitivity to individual rights.</p>
        <p>WILLIAM BETZ  Saipan, Northern Mariana Islands  Sept. 26, 2000</p>
      </block>
